** SSH to push git

You need to authenticate yourself before sending something to GitHub

You can create an SSH key, so GitHub recognizes you, then you can push your git

Key saved to: /home/john-doe/.ssh/id_ed25519

*Retrieving the password*
Paste this into the terminal to reveal the key -> cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub
From here copy the SSH key

*Connection to GitHub*
I now have an SSH key, which is linked to GitHub

** Issues I had before

When I create a repository on GitHub & added a README & or .gitignore (or ticked the boxes)
Then when I went to push my git repository, it caused an error, because GitHub already had a few files in it (the empty README & or .gitignore)

In future, don't add anything when creating the GitHub, add everything manually, locally
Then push the repository

** Commands to push a Repository

1. git init
2. git add .
3. git commit -m "initial commit"
4. git branch -M main
5. git remote add origin git@github.com:benwood256/<enter repository name>.git
6. git push -u origin main

If I accidentally connected to github & it's requesting my username:

   git remote set-url origin git@github.com:benwood256/<enter repository name>.git


